
[1]turbid

   TUR'BID, a. [L. turbidus, from turbo, to disturb,that is, to stir, to
   turn.] Properly, having the lees disturbed; but in a more general
   sense, muddy; foul with extraneous matter; thick; not clear; used of
   liquids of any kind; as turbid water; turbid wine. Streams running on
   clay generally appear to be turbid. This is often the case with the
   river Seine.
